    <article class="content-article">
      <p>I've replaced hundreds of thermal fuses in LG dryers, and nine times out of ten, the homeowner calls saying their dryer runs but won't heat up. That little $12 part - about the size of a quarter - is designed to blow when your dryer overheats, protecting your home from fire. When it goes bad, your LG stops heating completely.</p>
<h2>Signs Your LG Dryer Thermal Fuse Has Failed</h2>
<p>The most obvious sign is clothes coming out cold and damp after a full cycle. Your dryer will still tumble, the timer will count down normally, but there's zero heat. Some homeowners think it's the heating element, but we check the thermal fuse first - it's failed about 70% of the time in my experience. Another telltale sign is if your dryer was getting really hot before it stopped heating. That excessive heat is exactly what triggers the thermal fuse to blow. I've seen this pattern countless times in Pasadena and throughout LA County.</p>
<h3>Why LG Thermal Fuses Fail More Often</h3>
<p>LG dryers, especially the DLEX and DLGX series, tend to run hotter than other brands. The thermal fuse is located right in the blower housing where it gets hit with the hottest air. When your lint filter gets clogged or your exhaust vent is blocked, that fuse takes the heat and sacrifices itself. It's doing its job, but most people don't realize how quickly a blocked vent can cause this failure.</p>
<h2>Complete LG Dryer Thermal Fuse Replacement Process</h2>
<p>Replacing a thermal fuse isn't like changing a light bulb - there are real safety concerns. First, we always unplug the dryer and shut off the gas if it's a gas model. The thermal fuse sits on the blower housing, and getting to it means removing the top panel and front panel on most LG models. The tricky part isn't finding the fuse - it's making sure the wire connections are perfect. One loose connection and you're looking at arcing, which defeats the whole safety purpose. We use OEM LG parts exclusively because aftermarket fuses often have different temperature ratings.</p>
<h3>Tools Required for Professional Installation</h3>
<p>Beyond basic screwdrivers, we use a multimeter to test continuity and verify the new fuse is working correctly. A 1/4 inch nut driver is essential for most LG models, and we always have spare wire connectors in case the originals are corroded. The biggest mistake I see DIY attempts make is not testing the circuit before buttoning everything back up.</p>
<h3>Safety Precautions We Never Skip</h3>
<p>Every thermal fuse replacement starts with checking why the original failed. If we just swap the part without addressing a blocked vent or faulty heating element, the new fuse will blow within days. We always test the exhaust airflow and inspect the heating element assembly. This extra step is why our repairs stick - we fix the cause, not just the symptom.</p>
<h2>Testing Your LG Thermal Fuse with a Multimeter</h2>
<p>A multimeter tells the whole story with thermal fuses. Set it to continuity or the lowest ohms setting - a good thermal fuse should show zero resistance, basically a straight wire. A blown fuse shows infinite resistance or 'OL' on digital meters. But here's what most people miss: you need to test it while it's disconnected from the dryer. I've seen homeowners get confused readings because they're testing through other components in the circuit.</p>
<h3>Interpreting Multimeter Readings Correctly</h3>
<p>Zero ohms means the fuse is good - electricity flows through freely. Infinite resistance means it's blown and needs replacement. Sometimes you'll get a reading like 0.1 or 0.2 ohms, which is still considered good. The thermal fuse is either completely open or completely closed - there's no in-between like with other electrical components.</p>
<h2>LG Model Compatibility and Part Numbers</h2>
<p>Not all LG thermal fuses are the same, though they look nearly identical. The DLEX and DLGX series use different part numbers than the older LG models. We keep about 15 different LG thermal fuses in our truck because using the wrong one can create a safety hazard. The temperature rating is critical - some blow at 185°F, others at 200°F. Installing a higher-rated fuse might seem like it would prevent future failures, but it actually reduces the safety protection your dryer was designed with.</p>
<h3>Common LG Part Numbers We Stock</h3>
<p>The most common ones we install are 6931EL3001D for DLEX series and 6931EL3002A for many DLGX models. But honestly, we always verify the exact part number from your model's service manual rather than guessing. One wrong fuse installation and you're looking at potential fire risk or repeated failures.</p>
<h2>Preventing Future Thermal Fuse Failures</h2>
<p>The best way to protect your thermal fuse is keeping that exhaust vent clear. I can't count how many service calls in Irvine turned out to be lint blockages in the external vent. Check your outdoor vent hood monthly - if you can't feel strong airflow when the dryer's running, there's a blockage somewhere. Clean your lint filter before every load, not just when it looks full. Even a thin layer of lint reduces airflow enough to make your dryer work harder and run hotter.</p>
<h3>Warning Signs to Watch For</h3>
<p>If your dryer is taking longer to dry clothes or getting extremely hot on the outside, that thermal fuse is working overtime. Clothes that come out hotter than normal or a burning smell are red flags that you're headed for a thermal fuse failure. Address these issues immediately rather than waiting for the fuse to blow.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>How do I know if my LG dryer thermal fuse is blown?</h3>
<p>The dryer will run and tumble normally, but produce no heat at all. Your clothes come out cold and wet after a full cycle. We see this exact scenario probably three times a week - it's the most common thermal fuse symptom.</p>
<h3>Can I bypass the thermal fuse temporarily on my LG dryer?</h3>
<p>Don't do it. I've seen house fires from bypassed thermal fuses. That fuse is there to prevent your dryer from overheating and catching fire. Running without it is like disconnecting your smoke detector - technically possible but extremely dangerous.</p>
<h3>What causes LG dryer thermal fuses to fail repeatedly?</h3>
<p>Usually a blocked exhaust vent or a failing heating element that's drawing too much current. If we replace your thermal fuse and don't fix the underlying cause, you'll be calling us back in a few weeks. That's why we always check airflow and test the heating element.</p>
<h3>How much does it cost to replace an LG dryer thermal fuse?</h3>
<p>The part itself is around $15-20, but labor and diagnosis typically runs $120-150 total. We charge a $65 diagnostic fee that gets applied to the repair cost. Most thermal fuse replacements take about 45 minutes once we've identified the problem.</p>
<h3>Are LG thermal fuses interchangeable between different models?</h3>
<p>No, and this is where people get into trouble. A DLEX series fuse won't work safely in a DLGX model, even though they look identical. The temperature ratings are different. We always match the exact part number to your specific model to ensure proper safety protection.</p>
